text: hi everyone music review guy here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new billy
eilish album happier than ever this is a
brand new lp from one of contemporary
pop music's biggest stars billy eilish
two years or so after the release of her
excellent debut lp which i think was one
of the most unique and texturally
gratifying albums to come out of the
mainstream in a while i was kind of
neutral on her earlier output but that
album definitely turned me into a billy
eilish believer and someone who was
excited to see whatever her next album
would hold it was last year when billy
and her brother phineas began the
lengthy process of dropping singles that
would eventually end up on this lp i
mean the song my future spans all the
way back to the middle of last year the
track also sported this
sort of sophisticated dance pop style
and uh it's okay but it hasn't grown on
me too much since then but as we were
getting more and more singles there just
seemed to be little to no consistency or
cohesion to any of them the track
therefore i am for example was exactly
the kind of quirky dark ominous bedroom
pop that put billy on the map complete
with a sharp sense of humor and lyrics
that take shots with those who might be
trying to leech off of billy's
popularity or fandom there was also the
somber ballad your power which saw
acoustic guitars and atmospheric vocal
harmonies telling a story of abusing a
position of influence which i think is
pretty apt commentary in the metoo era
aesthetically the song is timely too in
a post phoebe bridger's world but
production wise in my opinion not as
daring as anything off of when we all
fall asleep which is sort of my general
issue with happier than ever it shows
billy and phineas trying their hands
stylistically at a variety of different
sounds but the overall experience is
somehow less unique and novel
than the last record it's not nearly as
cohesive either as this lengthier track
list flows and sprawls a lot more

so yes billy bossa nova one thing i will
say about the song though is that it
does deal in some of the most consistent
themes throughout the record being lust
temptation this is also mentioned to a
degree on the song my future which is a
song very much about being by yourself
loving yourself getting over getting out
of a relationship and allowing that to
give yourself some perspective and give
yourself some direction but there is
kind of that bridge portion of the song
where billy is flirting with the idea of
driving this person or someone home and
how that might tempt her to go back into
an old pattern that prevents her from
going down this new path there are also
more primal expressions of this on the
track oxytocin which is a total complete
and very sexual banger and production
wise sounds like what you would get if
uh pharrell williams produced a 9-inch
nail song from the 90s and i stand by
that [ __ ] comparison that's exactly
what it sounds like
there's the closing track male fantasy
whose intentions lyrics and obviously
title is a pretty self-explanatory and
the track not my responsibility some may
remember as that semi-ambient spoken
word piece that stirred so much
controversy when billy was performing it
live last year the piece is mostly a
commentary on the non-stop public
commentary on billy's clothes her looks
and a host of other things so the record
isn't completely random at least
thematically i wouldn't go as far as to
say this lp is a mess but again
musically and aesthetically the flow is
kind of inconsistent the whole thing
feels like a buffet of various music
styles some of which are kind of bland
to bring it back to not my
responsibility again as a four-minute
centerpiece for the lp it's a kind of
tedious listen even if i think the
statement and sentiment of the song is a
necessary one it also doesn't help that
the instrumental segues directly into
the following overheated it's more like
a musical extension with a mesmerizing
bee and massively half-baked lyrics i'm
overheated can't be defeated can't be
deleted can't be repeated but then the
following everybody dies even though i
like this track is one of many moments
on the lp as i'm listening through the
entire thing that feels like we're
hitting
the reset button and we're starting
aesthetically uh at square one once
again it's like a total switch up the
chords the dramatic progression the
frank lyricism honestly it kind of
sounds like some of phineas's recent
solo stuff which i guess again is not a
bad thing because i do think it is a
solid song and a pretty cool piece of
apocalyptic commentary but then once
more things switch up on that acoustic
single your power that i mentioned
earlier then there's the head scratching
nda which feels like a frankenstein
monster of a few different incomplete
ideas like the a section of the song
feels like something from billy's last
record but then it's paired with uh what
sounds like a sample from some terrible
world music sample pack
then you have this distorted yeezus type
instrumental build
with some auto-tuned vocals that runs
like a pre-chorus ascending towards
something but then there's not really
any
release or payoff past that point it
just kind of goes right back into the
verses musically and lyrically therefore
i am that i mentioned earlier is like
classic billy all the way but then
there's the title track which is one of
the most insane and surprising songs on
the entire record the whole thing starts
off like a very stripped back and quaint
1950 style acoustic ballad with the kind
of lo-fi guitars billy singing has a
vintage flair to it as well then
eventually the entire track just ascends
into this loud blaring distorted
chugging alt rock instrumental that's
like partially radiohead from the 90s
partially my chemical romance it's
abrasive but gutsy and a little bitter
too on the lyrical end it's giving
olivia rodrigo a run for her money in a
way which again this is another cool
moment on the lp it's just a little
annoying that my enjoyment of every
track here
just seems to be like on such a
case-by-case basis none of it ever feels
like it's coming together as a cohesive
piece or vision it's so scatter shot
which i guess would be fine if every
single song was fire from front to back
but that's not the case i would actually
say the track list on this one is a
little bloated with tracks that feel
like they could have been extended or
built out a little bit more layered a
bit more or just abandoned entirely
because they just come off a tad bit
bland we hear exactly this in the first
two songs of the record the opener is
intimate beautiful simple i love the
gentle hypnotic pumping organs just kind
of pulsating away in the background
billy's voice on top of them
sounds gorgeous and i think overall this
is a perfect tone setter for the lp but
then following this the i didn't change
my number has a surprising trip hop
twist to it and by comparison i think
instrumentally is a little bit too
dry and then there is that stuttering
distorted vocal or noise or something
that pops in suddenly on the back end
which i enjoy the song but i am still
like trying to reconcile that moment on
the track because it's abrasive it's not
mixed into the instrumental well seems
totally random and doesn't complement
the track at all look if we're talking
like on an individual basis there are a
lot of moments on this lp that i could
pick out and say hey here's a good song
here's a good song here's a highlight
here's a good track to me happier than
ever has a lot of the same great
qualities that billy's debut record did
but the creative tone on this lp feels a
lot more like billy and phineas just
throwing some caution to the wind trying
a bunch of different sounds and styles
and seeing what works and just letting
the chips fall where they may i guess
